		<div class="right"><a href="index.html"><img src="../sle.png" alt="SLE 2012"></a><br><code>sle2012/paper14</code></div>
			<h1><span class="less"><a href="index.html">SLE 2012</a> paper:</span><br><i>PAPAGENO: A Parallel Parser Generator for Operator Precedence Grammars</i></h1>
			<h2><a href="../profile/AlessandroBarenghi.html">Alessandro Barenghi</a>, <a href="../profile/ErmesViviani.html">Ermes Viviani</a>, <a href="../profile/StefanoCrespiReghizzi.html">Stefano Crespi Reghizzi</a>, <a href="../profile/DinoMandrioli.html">Dino Mandrioli</a>, <a href="../profile/MatteoPradella.html">Matteo Pradella</a></h2>
<ul><li>DOI: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_15">10.1007/978-3-642-36089-3_15</a></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t4a.html"><span class="tagM">T4A: Workbenches</span></a><ul><li> The central contribution is a parser generator that produces deterministic parallel parsers.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t5f.html"><span class="tagL">T5F: Performance</span></a><ul><li> Parallelization and measured speedups are primary concerns, making performance a key evaluation dimension.
</li></ul></li>
<li><a href="../tag/t3a.html"><span class="tagL">T3A: Meta-languages</span></a><ul><li> Operator-precedence grammars are the underlying formalism used to enable the generated parsers.
</li></ul></li></ul>
